      #appenddesc[fEMPRapRCH,"{b}Note:{/b}\nYou cannot use the teamwork feat class feature to replace Raptor Clan Heritage with a teamwork feat, or vice versa."]]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcEMPRapOC" name="Owl Clan" description="Members of your clan resemble owls when using their change shape ability. You gain a +2 racial bonus to Wisdom, and can use your Wisdom score (and Wisdom modifier) in place of your Charisma score (and Charisma modifier) for the purpose of any oracle class ability, including revelations and spells. You can select the Owl Clan Heritage feat with the oracle&apos;s revelation ability as if it was a revelation belonging to your chosen oracle mystery." compset="RaceCustom" summary="Appear as an owl when you shapechange, gain heritage as WIS-based oracle." uniqueness="useronce">
    <comment>When asked exactly how the “use your Wisdom score” effect works. the author had this to say, and therefore this is how I’ve best tried to implement this feature:

Ultimately, it&apos;s whatever interpretation the GM makes that matters.

Taken literally, you can use whichever score is highest at the time as your effective Charisma score for the purpose of oracle class abilities. Note that this effect alters your Charisma score, not the text of the oracle class itself. All of your oracle class features are still Charisma-based; you just get the option of setting your Charisma score equal to Wisdom score for the purpose of those Charisma-based features.

That last point is important because the Core Rules say ability damage &quot;does not actually reduce an ability, but it does apply a penalty to the skills and statistics that are based on that ability.&quot; Since your oracle class features are still technically Charisma-based, Charisma damage would penalize your oracle class features even if you are using your Wisdom score as your effective Charisma score. (Conversely, Wisdom damage would not penalize your oracle class features, because those features, as listed in the class description, are not Wisdom-based, despite your racial trait.)

On the other hand, ability drain and enhancement bonuses do change your ability scores. You apply ability drain and enhancement bonuses to your ability scores before deciding whether or not to use your (adjusted) Wisdom score in place of your (adjusted) Charisma score. So, if you invest in both Wisdom and Charisma, you end up getting a bit of a buffer against Charisma drain (but not against Charisma damage).</comment>
    <usesource source="EMPRaptor"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rEMPRaptCl"/>
    <eval phase="Validation" priority="500" index="3"><![CDATA[      ~ If we're not enabled, get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] <> 0)


      ~ Find the oracle class and set focus. If not found, get out
      perform hero.childfound[cHelpOra].setfocus
      doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

      focus.field[cCstS3Expr].text &= " | thingid.cOraEMPOwl"]]></eval>
    <eval phase="First" priority="200"><![CDATA[
      ~ If we're not enabled, get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] <> 0)

      ~ Find the race,change name and we get +2 WIS
      perform hero.findchild[BaseRace].setfocus
      doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

      focus.field[livename].text = field[thingname].text
      focus.field[rWIS].value += 2]]></eval>
    <eval phase="Attr" priority="1000005" index="2">~ If we&apos;re not enabled, get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] &lt;&gt; 0)


      ~ Find the oracle class and set focus. If not found, get out
      perform hero.childfound[cHelpOra].setfocus
      doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

      var Wis as number
      var Cha as number


      ~calculate the modifier difference between charisma and wisdom
      Wis = round (hero.childfound[aWIS].field[aFinalVal].value/2, 0, -1)
      Cha = round (hero.childfound[aCHA].field[aFinalVal].value/2, 0, -1)
      field[abValue].value += Wis - Cha
      field[abValue2].value += hero.childfound[aWIS].field[aFinalVal].value - hero.childfound[aCHA].field[aFinalVal].value


      ~ if our score change is 0 or negative, don’t touch
      doneif (field[abValue2].value &lt;= 0)


      ~ modify spellcasting attribute by difference, and allow Wisdom to determine maximum spell level
      focus.field[cSplAttVal].value += field[abValue2].value
      perform focus.assign[MaxSplAttr.aWIS]


      ~ if our modifier change is 0 or negative, don’t touch
      doneif (field[abValue].value &lt;= 0)


      ~ increase oracle abilities as if using WIS, if higher than CHA
      foreach pick in hero from BaseCustSp where &quot;CustTaken.cHelpOra &amp; (ChargeAttr.aCHA | StandardDC.aCHA)&quot;

        if (eachpick.tagis[StandardDC.aCHA] &lt;&gt; 0) then
            eachpick.field[abDC].value += field[abValue].value
            endif

        if (eachpick.tagis[ChargeAttr.aCHA] &lt;&gt; 0) then
            eachpick.field[trkMax].value += field[abValue].value
            endif

        nexteach</eval>
    </thing>
